  "prompt": "How and when ISS was send to space?",
  "response": "The **International Space Station (ISS)** was sent to space in multiple stages, beginning in **1998**. It was assembled in orbit through a series of over 40 missions involving spacecraft from the United States, Russia, and other international partners. Here's a timeline of key events:\n\n### 1. **First Module Launched (Zarya)**\n   - **Date**: **November 20, 1998**\n   - **Mission**: **Proton rocket** (Russia)\n   - The **Zarya** module, also known as the Functional Cargo Block, was the first component of the ISS. It provided power, propulsion, and storage.\n\n### 2. **Second Module Launched (Unity)**\n   - **Date**: **December 4, 1998**\n   - **Mission**: **Space Shuttle Endeavour** (NASA)\n   - The **Unity** module, also known as Node 1, was the first U.S.-built component. It was connected to Zarya during the STS-88 mission.\n\n### 3. **First Crew (Expedition 1)**\n   - **Date**: **November 2, 2000**\n   - **Mission**: **Soyuz TM-31** (Russia)\n   - The **first permanent crew**, consisting of **William Shepherd** (NASA), **Yuri Gidzenko** (Roscosmos), and **Sergei Krikalev** (Roscosmos), arrived at the ISS. This marked the beginning of continuous human habitation on the station.\n\n### 4. **Assembly and Expansion**\n   - Over the next decade, additional modules, trusses, and solar arrays were added to the ISS:\n     - **Zvezda** (Russia, 2000): The service module, providing living quarters and life support.\n     - **Destiny Laboratory** (NASA, 2001): The primary U.S. research module.\n     - **European Columbus Laboratory** (ESA, 2008).\n     - **Japanese Kibo Laboratory** (JAXA, 2008).\n   - The assembly was completed in **2011** with the installation of the final module, **Rassvet**.\n\n### 5. **Current Status**\n   - The ISS orbits Earth at an altitude of approximately **400 kilometers (250 miles)** and travels at a speed of about **28,000 kilometers per hour (17,500 mph)**. It is the largest human-made object in space and serves as a **microgravity laboratory** for scientific research and international cooperation.\n\nThe ISS is a joint project involving **NASA (U.S.)**, **Roscosmos (Russia)**, **ESA (Europe)**, **JAXA (Japan)**, and **CSA (Canada)**. It remains a symbol of global collaboration in space exploration.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
